d_gap_text": "", "similarity": null}, "passed": true}, "short_span_min_tokens": {"details": {"min_tokens": 2, "token_count": 255}, "passed": true}}, "text": "III. THE WEST\n\nArmy Officers Considering Coup Against Salvadoran President\n\nA group of Salvadoran lieutenant colonels has recently been meeting with two members of the National Legislative Assembly, General Quintanilla and Captain Buitrago--both of whom are trying to persuade the officers to lead a coup against President Lemus in the second week of April. The proposed coup is intended to capitalize on the growing discontent among the military with the policies of President Lemus. The President, however, is probably aware of some plotting, since he ordered the transfer of 19 high-ranking officers on 29 March, perhaps to disrupt a plot.\n\nThe most recent irritant to the military is a new law limiting the number of generals and colonels in the Salvadoran Army to eight generals and forty colonels. Past dissatisfaction has stemmed partly from disgruntlement at not receiving the favorable treatment accorded the military by previous presidents and their belief that Lemus is grooming Major Rubio Melhado as presidential candidate for the 1962 elections.\n\na palace revolution was a \"certainty\" if the President persists in championing Melhado as his successor.\n\nThe anti-Communist officer corps, however, may be hesitant about taking advice from Quintanilla and Buitrago, whose actions in the National Legislative Assembly would favor Communists and sympathizers with Fidel Castro's revolutionary movement in the elections to be held on 24 April. Neither Quintanilla nor Buitrago was renominated as a candidate. The Communists, who are reported to have recently received a shipment of arms, may attempt to stir up violence before and after the election", "token_count": 255, "token_end_0based": 254, "token_start_0based": 0, "token_text": "iii the west army officers considering coup against salvadoran president a group of salvadoran lieutenant colonels has recently been meeting with two members of the national legislative assembly general quintanilla and captain buitrago both of whom are trying to persuade the officers to lead a coup against president lemus in the second week of april the proposed coup is intended to capitalize on the growing discontent among the military with the policies of president lemus the president however is probably aware of some plotting since he ordered the transfer of 19 high-ranking officers on 29 march perhaps to disrupt a plot the most recent irritant to the military is a new law limiting the number of generals and colonels in the salvadoran army to eight generals and forty colonels past dissatisfaction has stemmed partly from disgruntlement at not receiving the favorable treatment accorded the military by previous presidents and their belief that lemus is grooming major rubio melhado as presidential candidate for the 1962 elections a palace revolution was a certainty if the president persists in championing melhado as his successor the anti-communist officer corps however may be hesitant about taking advice from quintanilla and buitrago whose actions in the national legislative assembly would favor communists and sympathizers with fidel castro's revolutionary movement in the elections to be held on 24 april neither quintanilla nor buitrago was renominated as a candidate the communists who are reported to have recently received a shipment of arms may attempt to stir up violence before and after the election", "unred_source_page": 14}
